My newborn work continues to evolve into something more raw and real. To be invited into someones home during such an intimate time is such an honor. ⁠
⁠
I have been working with newborns in one way or another since I was 22 years old and I hope I am working with them another 20 plus years. ⁠
⁠
I leave my newborn sessions absolutely buzzing from the oxytocin in the air (yes, that is a thing, you can literally feel the oxytocin in the air when there is a new baby around.) ⁠
⁠
Such a gift. Such an honor.⁠
⁠
My newborn work has ZERO to do with putting your baby into an unnatural and unsafe pose and everything to do with capturing THIS. ⁠
⁠
Cause I am here to tell ya, time is a thief. And while I remember what it was like to be in this exact same spot, on my bed with my three babies under the age of six piled on my lap, I can hardly believe that I now lay my head on my sons chest when I hug him and look eye to eye with my twelve year old. And my baby is a precocious eight year old ready to run the world. ⁠
⁠
It is my job to make photos for you that will take you right back to THIS. The slow first few days at home navigating breastfeeding, and tantrums, and snacks, and hurt feelings, and jealousy, and love, and smothering, and every single feeling you can think of. THAT is the stuff of life. ⁠
⁠
God I love my job.

I get asked a lot from students who are in Lifestyle Newborn Photography Made Easy how I get my clients to relax and allow for nursing photos and the answer is actually pretty simple....⁠
⁠
I share nursing photos on my social media and on my website. So my clients are expecting it. ⁠
⁠
That being said, before I bring the camera up to take the nursing photo I say "is it okay with you if I capture you nursing?" ⁠
⁠
That simple. ⁠
⁠
You also have to feel the vibe of the mama. You will likely be able to tell if the mother is okay with it. ⁠
⁠
I also take photos of babies being fed with bottles as well. It's really the intimacy of feeding that is being captured, breast or bottle, it's all beautiful.

I want to lift you up and support you. ⁠
⁠
I want to help you reach your fullest potential. ⁠
⁠
I want to teach you new ways to visualize and realize the life of your dreams. ⁠
⁠

Twelve years later I can say without a doubt she was right.

I don't do a New Years resolution per say- I do like words however. I know, I know, so does everyone else on Instagram. I get it, kinda basic. But it helps. This year it is more of a phrase. ⁠
⁠
I had a dream about a month back, and in my head a phrase came through. It was in my voice and when I woke up in the early morning hours I heard it again...⁠
⁠
"Let it be easy"⁠
⁠
I spend a lot of time complicating things, taking on new projects, or over thinking things. I worry the rug will be pulled out from under me and that I will be left with nothing. But none of that actually serves me. All that does is make things harder and gets me out of flow and out of trust. ⁠
⁠
So this year I am going to Let It Be Easy and trust that I have done a lot of the work already and that I can enjoy the ebbs and flows of this life. ⁠
⁠
Today is my first day back to work in 17 days. Wish me luck on living this phrase out today. 😩⁠
⁠
Happy New Year, friend! It's good to be back!

I just finished up my last round of 1/1 calls with my Mastermind students today. And you know what we mostly talked about???⁠
⁠
Life. ⁠
⁠
Not business. Not art. But life. ⁠
⁠
Here is why I think that is... ⁠
⁠
For one, The Mastermind worked. They have the tools they need to move forward. They have made more money, found more artistic alignment, found meaning in their photography business, and most importantly, built a community. ⁠
⁠
But really it's because at the end of the day we are all just humans "walking each other home." And the reason we find each other is because we need mirrors to show us what is possible. ⁠
⁠
This is a photo of me and my three when I was in full on warrior mode. My dear friend @elizabethanderson_photographer took this and coincidence would have it she was also in warrior mode.⁠
⁠
I was a single mom. I was living alone for the first time in my whole life. I was supporting my family all by myself. And I was scared AF. ⁠
⁠
But I knew one thing and one thing only... I was going to get through it for THEM. For my three diamonds. And I did just that. Sometimes it meant crying on the closet floor after they went to bed. Sometimes it meant escaping my life with a random 24 hour trip to Miami or NYC. But I did it. We did it. ⁠
⁠
When I see this photo I can tell that I was casting my shadow on them a bit. I couldn't help it. It was so hard. But I can also see that together, we got through it. And that we are all thriving now. ⁠
⁠
So all that to say... To my Mastermind community (and to you) I see the human in you and thank you for seeing the human in me.⁠
⁠
As the quote by Ram Dass says:⁠
⁠
"We are all just walking each other home." ⁠

I struggled with breastfeeding with two out of three of my babies. I remember holding a screaming baby in my arms, tears running down my own face, wondering why it was so hard, why I couldn't get my baby to latch. I remember curling my toes in agony just to hold back whimpering when one of my babies latched because it hurt so bad. ⁠
⁠
It was hard. ⁠
⁠
But I stuck it out and went on to nurse all of my babies well past their second or even third birthdays. Turns out I was that mom. Who knew? ⁠
⁠
All that to say... I think breastfeeding hardship is one of those things we don't talk about enough. So while I love to celebrate it and photograph it I want it to be clear that I know not everyone has an easy breastfeeding journey and I know that not everyone chooses to breastfeed at all and especially into toddlerhood like I did. And that is okay. ⁠
⁠
How you mother your baby is your choice and your choice alone. And guess what, breastfeeding is hard and beautiful and exhausting and emotional and painful and peaceful and so many things. ⁠
⁠

What would you want to remember? Ask yourself that when setting out to photograph a newborn and their family.⁠
⁠
Something tells me that you wouldn't want to look back and see your perfect baby in someone else's bunny costume, propped up in an unnatural (and unsafe) way, folded into a pose that is called taco, with editing to make them look like a doll. ⁠
⁠
Babies enter this world beautiful and full of wonder. Sure sometimes they have flakey skin and you can see the adorable hair that grows on their ears an back... but that is part of what makes them beautiful. Why would we remove that in editing?⁠
⁠
You want to remember how they smelled. How they sounded. How they felt all wrapped up in your arms. You want to remember how your doggie couldn't' get enough of your new baby. You want to remember how bad you wanted that baby and how amazing it felt to have him in your arms. ⁠
⁠
I am in the feelings business. And my job is to make you feel with my art. Not see. ⁠

I have been doing 1/1 calls with my my mastermind members and we are talking a lot about "brand." The concept of a brand is very commonly misunderstood for most. ⁠
⁠
My guess is that you think brand has everything to do with logo and fonts and color pallet. But those are the LEASET important things about your brand, and the most boring things if you ask me! ⁠
⁠
A lot of photographers get caught up on how their work and brand looks and not how it feels. And when they do that they lack clarity. So their brand becomes muddy and it becomes very hard to market themselves. ⁠
⁠
Your work should always feel like you, regardless of what or who you are photographing. ⁠
⁠
Brand clarity is a very complex topic, actually. Luckily I get five solid months with my members and after four successful cohorts behind me I can say that my members leave the Mastermind with far more clarity then when they started. ⁠
⁠
So ask yourself, does your work have a consistent feeling?
If you could ask me one question about my approach to Lifestyle Newborn Photography, what would it be? GO!!! 👇🏼
Spoiler alert.... babies cry. It is okay to capture all the ranges of emotions in your teeny subjects. In fact, mama and papa will thank you for it. ❤️

Allow me to bust some myths when it comes to newborn photography!

I used to think that in order to make money as a newborn photographer I had to pose babies and use props. I wasted so many hours trying to get babies to sleep in order to pose them in ways that I saw others doing. ⁠
⁠
It wasn't until I had my third baby that I realized posing babies was completely out of alignment with who I am as an artist and who I am as a person.⁠
⁠
Babies are perfect and beautiful as they are. They don't need to be overfed in order to make them sleep so that you can place them in unnatural poses. ⁠
⁠
My approach to newborn photography focuses on the simple beauty that is a newborn baby and the connection that they have with their family.⁠
⁠
I show up to my newborn sessions with my @canonusa 5d MIV with a 50mm 1.2L and my R5 with a 35mm lens and that is all. ⁠
⁠
No lights. ⁠
No props.⁠
No wraps. ⁠
No posing aids.⁠
⁠
Babies don't need to be made into something that they aren't to be beautiful. I promise.

Last May, I shared the following words... the last time some of OUR children were shot at school. SCHOOL, where they go to learn and grow and play and be kids. So I am sharing the exact words again cause not one thing as changed and we have let it happen again. From May 26th 2022:⁠
⁠
"When you become a mother you join a sisterhood. A global community of other humans who completely understand the daunting task that is raising a child. ⁠
⁠
And when you become a mother, instantly, every other child also becomes yours. If you see a child about to fall at the park, you reach out to catch them. If you see a child who is lost, you stop and help them find their mama. If you hear a baby cry on a plane it takes every ounce of your being not to get up and offer to hold that baby for a while. ⁠
⁠
I have spent the last week literally surrounded by the strong, protective, and communal maternal energy that I am speaking of. From a Mothers Blessing where I got to bask in the loving support of my best friend and her best friends to a road trip with two of my dearest friends where we shared stories of raising humans in our world, to a dinner out with my blood sisters who have very much been like mothers to me my whole life. ⁠
⁠
I am surrounded by this love. And my children are too. ❤️⁠
⁠
So to hear the news that some of OUR CHILDREN were murdered, AGAIN, at school, broke my heart into a million pieces. Just like I know it did every other mother on this planet who, like I said, are part of this sisterhood and knows that our job is to protect all of our children. But we couldn't. We didn't. And I am ashamed that I live in a country that won't. ⁠
⁠
I had to hear my 14 year old son say "this sucks and it's sad but sadly nothing is going to change."⁠
⁠
Shame on us. ⁠
⁠
I feel completely helpless but I have vowed to at least do something when these things happen. Today I will be sharing in stories a few things you can do NOW to at least speak up about this. ⁠
⁠
I love you. Thank you for being here."⁠
⁠
I feel deflated. Helpless. And scared for our children. Enough already. And yes, I do want to take away your guns. All of them.

Today is my beautiful mothers 81st birthday. And these are photos of us the day I was born. 🥰⁠
⁠
Our Mother is the kind of mother all of us aspire to be. She loves us fiercely and literally gave her whole life for us. We were everything to her and we knew it. We still know it. That's a kind of love that everyone deserves and we have it. Ten fold. ⁠
⁠
She wanted us girls to be strong and independent and told us every single day that we could be anything we wanted to be. ⁠
⁠
And we believed her. ⁠
⁠
She cooked us breakfast, lunch, and dinner, nearly every day and eating around the table at dinner time was a non negotiable, even if we brought friends and boyfriends to the table, which we often did, she fed them too- something that I do with my own family now, remembering how important it was to unwind with my family each day. ⁠
⁠
She stayed up late helping us type essays, made sure we always had what we needed to feel like we fit in, went to every single competition and event I ever had, stayed up crying with me when my heart was broken, and was by my side each time I welcomed a baby into this world, reminding me that she had birthed me without meds and if she could do it so could I. ⁠
⁠
And I believed her. ⁠
⁠

Let's talk about the biggest obstacle every photographer faces: lack of confidence. ⁠
⁠
It's a struggle we all share, especially in this era of social media where comparison becomes inevitable. Here are a few tips to start building your confidence NOW! ⁠

1. First things first, trust your own magic! 🌟 Embrace the fact that no two photographers see the world the same way. You have a unique creative gift that needs to be shared with the world. YES YOU! ⁠

⁠
Take your camera everywhere, take photos of everyone and everything that catches your eye. If you're ready to launch your photography business, do model calls and practice with real people for free. Experiment with different lighting conditions and locations. The more you practice, the more confidence will blossom within you. ⁠
⁠
3. Invest in yourself and your craft by joining photography workshops or classes. Online workshops offer affordability and flexibility, allowing you to learn at your own pace. If you crave real-time feedback and live instruction, in-person workshops are worth the investment, albeit a bit pricier. If you want long term coaching, join a Mastermind (ahem, mine is open for applications now.) Remember, every class you take will add to your knowledge and boost your confidence. You'll never regret investing in yourself and your passion. 🌈💡⁠
⁠
Trust me, if I can do it, so can you. You were meant for this. I promise! ⁠

By the end of the summer the teenagers will outnumber the rest of us in the house. My role as a mother is shifting greatly. Gone are the days where I am pacing the halls with a fussy baby or where a bandaid can cure all ailments. My kids can be left alone physically for hours but the emotional support they need is greater than ever. ⁠
⁠
Teenagers are on an emotional rollercoaster ride every single day and as a compassionate mother you want to get in the seat next to them and strap in... ride right along with them, holding their hand and screaming your head off with them. ⁠
⁠
But you can't. ⁠
⁠
You have to stay on the ground and watch them go up and down over and over again, holding your breath and just hopping that those safety straps work how they are supposed to, allowing them to experience the ride for all of it's exhilarating highs and it's painfully low lows. ⁠
⁠
You just have to be a steady place to come home to after the exhaustion of experiencing it all, a solid hand to hold, a safe place to land, a sympathetic ear.⁠
⁠
You just have to hope that you raised them with the resilience to get through it, the integrity to appreciate it, and the trust that they will come to you when they really need you. You have to hope that you have put up enough guard rails so they can ride the ride with their hands in the air while also staying safely secure when they go upside down. ⁠
⁠
Needless to say... parenting teens ins't for the faint of heart. But I am sincerely enjoying the ride. A lot of my clients are entering this stage of parenting too and it's been such a joy to capture it.

I used to think I was a bad writer. I remember the anxiety I felt in my first language arts class my freshman year of college. I spent hours upon hours on the first essay and when I got it back from the professor it looked like it was bleeding. ⁠
⁠
It was later in that year that another professor said to me "I think you have learning disabilities." WHAT? But also. Well now this all makes sense. That was the year I finally learned I have ADHD and also Dyslexia. ⁠
⁠
But it would take me many years to feel like I was safe or free to write. I have been a journal keeper since I was in 1st grade, truly. And that has always felt so good. Just getting it all down on paper. But I never felt I was smart enough to share my words. And truth be told, I still get a little anxious when I write from the heart or when I speak up at a dinner table full of intelligent people. I am extremely defensive when someone makes me feel stupid... which is likely not their fault and just my deep insecurities about it all. I spent my whole childhood feeling like I was the stupid one in class or among some of my sisters and those wounds cut deep.⁠
⁠
Anyway...I did what so many mothers did in the early 2000's and I started a mom blog. Yup I did that. Don't judge. 😂 That was when I said "to hell with grammar and criticism." Now, I just type like I talk and I share from the heart. ❤️ I get at least one email or DM a week calling out my grammar errors. Don't care. 😆⁠
⁠
All this to say- you have something inside of you. And that something needs to be let out. I only wish I was encouraged to not just be "smart" but to also be "creative." My power has always been in my creativity, but nobody told me I should tap into creativity. Nobody. ⁠
⁠
One of the things I am most proud of as a mother is how creative all of my children are. Like SO PROUD. They are all part of performing arts and they are all creative in other ways as well. Because I strongly believe that creativity is as important as literacy. ⁠
⁠
You are so much more than you know and your creative gifts need to be shared with the world. For that I am certain. Keeping them inside will only hurt you in the end.

If you feel overwhelmed and like you are too busy, ask yourself what parts of your life are out of alignment and see what you can do to realign them. 

Create a designer life. Because, as far as we know, you only live once. Make it a good one. 💫
